const faqSchema = { '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'FAQPage', mainEntity: [
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is sambucus elderberry?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Sambucus nigra (European black elderberry) is the specific species of elderberry with the most extensive clinical research supporting immune health benefits. The term "sambucus" on supplement labels indicates the product uses this clinically validated species rather than other elderberry varieties. Sambucus nigra berries contain high concentrations of anthocyanins — dark purple flavonoid antioxidants that have demonstrated direct antiviral activity against influenza viruses in laboratory studies. A 2019 meta-analysis in Complementary Therapies in Medicine analyzed 4 RCTs and found that elderberry supplementation significantly reduced the duration and severity of upper respiratory infections, particularly common cold and influenza.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How does elderberry support the immune system?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Elderberry supports immune function through multiple mechanisms. First, its anthocyanins have demonstrated direct antiviral activity — a 2019 study in the Journal of Functional Foods showed elderberry compounds bind to and prevent the entry of influenza H1N1 virus into host cells. Second, elderberry stimulates cytokine production, enhancing the immune system\'s inflammatory response to pathogens. Third, elderberry contains vitamins A and C, both of which support immune cell function. Fourth, the antioxidant activity of elderberry compounds helps protect immune cells from oxidative damage during infection. These mechanisms work together to both prevent viral entry and enhance the body\'s immune defense once infection begins.' } },
