    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Sambucus Elderberry Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is sambucus elderberry?</summary><p>Sambucus nigra is the European black elderberry species with the most clinical research. Its anthocyanins have demonstrated antiviral activity and immune-stimulating properties in multiple RCTs.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How does elderberry support the immune system?</summary><p>Through anthocyanin antiviral activity, cytokine stimulation, antioxidant protection of immune cells, and natural vitamin A and C content.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much elderberry should I take daily?</summary><p>300-600mg extract for prevention, 600-1,200mg for acute use during illness (3-5 days). Look for standardized anthocyanin content.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Is elderberry safe to take every day?</summary><p>Daily use during cold/flu season is generally safe. People with autoimmune conditions should consult their physician due to elderberry's cytokine-stimulating effects.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does elderberry really reduce cold duration?</summary><p>A meta-analysis of 4 RCTs found elderberry reduced URI duration by 1.86 days and severity scores. Most effective when started within 24-48 hours of symptom onset.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Should elderberry gummies include zinc and vitamin C?</summary><p>Yes — zinc reduces cold duration by 33% and vitamin C by 8%. The triple combination addresses immune defense through three complementary mechanisms.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can children take elderberry gummies?</summary><p>Most are formulated for ages 4+. Zarbee's offers pediatric versions for ages 2+. Children under 2 should not take elderberry. Consult a pediatrician for children with autoimmune conditions.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the difference between extract and powder?</summary><p>Extract is concentrated and standardized for consistent anthocyanin delivery. Powder is the dried whole berry — less concentrated. Most clinical trials used extract.</p></details>

    <div class="warn-box"><span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span><p><strong>Important:</strong> Never consume raw or uncooked elderberries — they contain cyanogenic glycosides that can cause nausea and vomiting. Only use commercially prepared elderberry supplements. People with autoimmune conditions should consult their physician before taking elderberry due to its cytokine-stimulating effects. Elderberry is a supplement, not a replacement for flu vaccination or antiviral medication.</p></div>

